1️⃣ Setup & Configuration
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"
git config --list
Used once when setting up Git.
2️⃣ Creating / Cloning Repository
git init
→ Initializes a new local repo
git clone 
→ Copies remote repository to your system
Example:
git clone https://github.com/user/project.git⁠�
3️⃣ Checking Status & Changes
git status
→ Shows modified, staged, untracked files
git diff
→ Shows changes not staged
git diff --staged
→ Shows staged changes
4️⃣ Staging & Committing
git add filename
→ Add specific file
git add .
→ Add all files
git commit -m "message"
→ Commit with message
git commit -am "message"
→ Add + commit (only tracked files)
5️⃣ Branching (Very Important in Client Projects)
git branch
→ List branches
git branch new-branch
→ Create branch
git checkout new-branch
→ Switch branch
git checkout -b new-branch
→ Create + switch
git switch branch-name
→ Modern way to switch
Enterprise Tip: Never commit directly to main/master unless instructed.
6️⃣ Remote Operations
git remote -v
→ Show remote URLs
git pull
→ Fetch + merge changes
git fetch
→ Download changes (no merge)
git push origin branch-name
→ Push branch
Example: git push origin feature/login-module
7️⃣ Merging & Rebasing
git merge branch-name
→ Merge branch into current branch
git rebase branch-name
→ Reapply commits on top of another branch
Important: Rebase rewrites history. Be careful in shared branches.